Data Acquisition

Author

Shahrokh Vahedi

1 Challenge: Get Data via an API

In this code, occurrence data for the honeybee species was fetched using the GBIF API. The latitude and longitude of the occurrences were then plotted on a map of the world using the ggplot2 and maps packages in R. The resulting plot (Fig. 1) shows the distribution of honeybee occurrences (the fetched data is primarily for America continent).

# Scrape one of the competitor websites of canyon (either https://www.rosebikes.de/ or https://www.radon-bikes.de) and create a small database

Unfortunately, I was not able to get the hang of html structure and do scraping. So I will leave this part Blank

2 Source code

# Load required libraries
library(httr)
library(jsonlite)

# Define API endpoint and parameters
api_url <- "https://api.gbif.org/v1/occurrence/search"
params <- list(
  taxonKey = 2435098, # Taxon key for the species (e.g., 2435098 for "Apis mellifera" - the honeybee)
  limit = 300         # Number of records to fetch (max 300)
)

# Send GET request to the API
response <- GET(api_url, query = params)



# Check the HTTP status code
status_code <- status_code(response)
if (status_code == 200) {
  # Successful response
  print("Request successful!")
  # Parse JSON response
  json_data <- content(response, as = "text", encoding = "UTF-8")
  data <- fromJSON(json_data, flatten = TRUE)
  
  # Convert the results to a dataframe
  occurrences_df <- as.data.frame(data$results)
  
  # Print the dataframe
  print(occurrences_df)
} else {
  # Unsuccessful response
  print(paste("Request failed with status code:", status_code))
}

#> 19  Using my hand for comparison, I made measurements on the screen and solved for X. I measured the total length of an adult domestic cat skull at 90 mm, an adult male Bobcat at 123 mm, and your skull at 151 mm. Since the cranium of your skull is broken, I also measured from the anterior edge of the premaxilla to the posterior edge of the occipital condyle and found this measurement to be proportionately consistent with the total length measurement. Since Bobcats lack the small upper premolar, this skull only needed to be larger than a domestic cat. In fact, it is larger than a large male Bobcat. Your skull is just about 6 inches long, so I am confident it is a Mountain Lion. This is a much more interesting find. @maxallen

#> 120                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   Is Puma Concolor a designated subspecies or a subpopulation? Lions can be identified by some genetic markers based on geography, (10 different genetic markers based on geography in California alone), but it is not enough to qualify as a “subspecies”. The general agreement among scientist is that there are not any subspecies of Puma Concolor.

#> 224                                                                                       Lions can be identified by some genetic markers based on geography, (10 different genetic markers based on geography in California alone), but it is not enough to qualify as a “subspecies”. According to the Cat News, the newsletter of the Cat Specialist Group which is a component of the Species Survival Commission of the International Union for Conservation of Nature in 2017 they state that Puma concolor was split into 32 subspecies (1946). As of 2014 they did recognize North and South American subspecies but with a low mtDNA sample size. The general agreement among scientist today is that there are not any subspecies of Puma Concolor.

#> 261                                                                              Lions can be identified by some genetic markers based on geography, (10 different genetic markers based on geography in California alone), but it is not enough to qualify as a “subspecies”. According to the Cat News, the newsletter of the Cat Specialist Group which is a component of the Species Survival Commission of the International Union for Conservation of Nature in 2017 they state that Puma concolor was split into 32 subspecies in 1946. As of 2014 they did recognize North and South American subspecies but with a low mtDNA sample size. The general agreement among scientist today is that there are not any genetic subspecies of Puma Concolor.

# Load required libraries
library(ggplot2)
library(ggmap)
#> i Google's Terms of Service: <https://mapsplatform.google.com>
#> i Please cite ggmap if you use it! Use `citation("ggmap")` for details.
library(maps)

# Remove rows with missing latitude or longitude
occurrences_df <- occurrences_df[!is.na(occurrences_df$decimalLatitude) & !is.na(occurrences_df$decimalLongitude),]

# Get the world map data
world_map <- map_data("world")

# Create a ggplot object with the world map
map_plot <- ggplot() +
  geom_polygon(data = world_map, aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group), fill = "gray80", color = "gray50") +
  theme_minimal()

# Add the scatter plot of latitude and longitude on top of the map
map_plot + geom_point(data = occurrences_df, aes(x = decimalLongitude, y = decimalLatitude), color = "blue", alpha = 0.5) +
  labs(title = "Bio-diversity of Honey Bees", x = "Longitude", y = "Latitude")
